Anonymous Tue 07 Nov 2023 13:36:02 No.60938118 Report
Quoted By: >>60938819
>>60936913
>Does Stable Diffusion take up much space on your computer? Does it cause it to overheat much.

Space: Not really a lot to get you in the door. As you would expect, the software isn't large, but the data is. Stable Diffusion models run about 2GB each. (Though they will often come at 4GB; you can cut them down from 32 bit to 16 bit yourself and have no difference in output but when you're training models you want those extra decimals.) It's easy to start hording model variations and you usually shouldn't. (Though if you don't trust Big Bother and Big Tech you might fear the AI crackdown that will someday disappear everything that isn't approved by your masters.) Also, you get more specialized models for upscaling and extensions like ControlNet, which will easily add another 20 GB to your install. Storage is cheap, don't suffer under an almost full drive.

Time: Graphics card determines comfort and limits. More VRAM, bigger initial gens. You can go CPU-based and you can work around with low VRAM but it's a lot of work, at some point you're better off spending that time mowing lawns after your day job and buying the better video card.

Heat: More horsepower, faster generation. Heat usually isn't an issue but you want to watch your numbers for a while at first. Don't trust the thermal automatic throttling, that's more like a fuse or breaker, people who have relied on it to stop them have regretted it. But if you're staying in the 70's you can probably run without concern.

Skinner box: Early, you're delighted to get it to work at all. Then you get what you want and share it and people bitch and call it slop. It's someone gets a tablet or a how-to-anime book and seeks approval but the audience finds it tiresome. Good AI requires learning the system, having enough art brain to notice problems and inpaint them away, and make actual art using that tool. And we've seen pro artists ruin their reputations by using it as a shortcut.
